title: U.S. Defense Secretary Blames Iraqi Forces for ISIS Victory in Ramadi
description: In some of the administration’s strongest remarks yet, Ashton B. Carter said Iraqi troops “failed to fight,” blaming them for a retreat that led to the fall of Ramadi to the Islamic State.

title: John F. Nash Jr., Mathematician Whose Life Story Inspired ‘A Beautiful Mind,’ Dies at 86
description: The narrative of Mr. Nash’s brilliant rise, the lost years of severe mental illness, and the eventual awarding of a Nobel Prize captured the public mind.

title: Defendants Using Biographical Videos to Show Judges Another Side at Sentencing
description: Defense lawyers are embracing video as a way to help them tell what they hope will be a more favorable story about their clients.

title: No Rest for Arlington National Cemetery’s Minders of Details
description: The most solemn sentiments of the Memorial Day holiday have long been infused in the work done at Arlington National Cemetery throughout the year.

title: Mower Meets Moonshine at a Shrine for George Jones
description: The George Jones Museum has one boot in the old Nashville and one in the new, reflecting a city being remade with gleaming towers and one where country music is part of the DNA.

title: Malaysia Finds Graves of Suspected Trafficking Victims
description: The Malaysian home minister says police have discovered mass graves of suspected trafficking victims near the country's border with Thailand.

title: Peace Activists Cross Demilitarized Zone Separating Koreas
description: Gloria Steinem was among a group of 30 female peace activists who crossed by bus on Sunday from North Korea to South Korea, calling for an end to unresolved hostility.

title: At Least 10 Afghan Police Officers Killed in Taliban Assault
description: Officials in Afghanistan say at least 10 police officers have been killed in an ongoing Taliban assault in the country's volatile south.

title: Warriors 115, Rockets 80: Stephen Curry, With a Little Help, Tramples the Rockets
description: Curry, who dazzled the crowd into a state of bewilderment, finished with 40 points as the Warriors seized a three-games-to-none lead in the Western Conference finals.

title: Saudis Say ISIS Ordered Suicide Bombing of Mosque
description: The suicide bombing on Friday killed at least 21 worshipers at a Shiite mosque in a town near Qatif, in the Eastern Province.

title: Ethiopia’s Ruling Party Is Expected to Keep Grip on Power
description: The Ethiopian People’s Revolutionary Democratic Front has been in power for 24 years. Given its influence in rural areas, it is likely to win again in Sunday’s national election.

title: With Victories, ISIS Dispels Hope of a Swift Decline
description: In its conquest of Ramadi and new control of Palmyra, the Islamic State has shown how dedication to its core principles helped it regain traction.

title: Republican Rivals Skirt Specifics on Plans to Fight ISIS
description: A picture has emerged of a field of declared and likely candidates that sound hawkish about fighting the Islamic State, yet are reluctant and even evasive when it comes to laying out detailed plans.

title: Body Found in Hudson River Near Where Kayaker Disappeared
description: The unidentified body was transported to the Orange County morgue, where an autopsy will be performed, the police said.

title: Tree Project Aims to Put the Oak Back in Oakland
description: A campaign to “re-oak” Oakland has begun, which started when volunteers planted an inaugural stand of 72 coast live oak saplings in plastic buckets in a West Oakland park.

title: 3 Decades After Hate Crime, Ireland’s Gay Population Hails Vote
description: The killing of a gay man that produced a movement also led to a distinction for Ireland: It is the only country to legalize same-sex marriage by popular vote.

title: Decade After Katrina, Pointing Finger More Firmly at Army Corps
description: An article by experts involved in some previous examinations of the catastrophe contends that fault should fall squarely on the Army Corps of Engineers.

title: First Draft: Hillary Clinton to Hold Fund-Raiser Hosted by Spitzer’s Ex-Wife
description: Hillary Rodham Clinton will hold a string of fund-raisers on June 1, including one hosted by the ex-wife of Eliot Spitzer, the scandal-plagued former governor of New York.

title: Egyptian Court Acquits 17 in Case Arising From Poet’s Death at March
description: The charges and unexpected acquittals underscored the increasingly capricious nature of Egypt’s justice system under its military-backed government.

title: Pakistani Journalists Resign to Cut Ties to Axact, a Fake Diploma Company
description: The defections came hours after the interior minister said that a preliminary investigation conducted last week had uncovered evidence against Axact.
